description:
Reviewing the new Asus Prime OC Geforce RTX 5060, and comparing it to an RTX 2080 Ti from 2018.

Nvidia's new entry level Geforce in the 50 series is the 8GB RTX 5060, with a $299 MSRP and UK selling prices starting at £269. The RTX 2080 Ti was the flagship of the Turing series, with a $999 MSRP and retail prices going significantly higher than that. Has the last 7 years of development brought flagship performance down to the masses? Is 8GB really enough, and can the older card's 11GB help it win this head-to-head?

Thanks to Asus UK for the review sample

Yes, the die slice represents a portion of a wafer. comments.text:
You just need to look at the chips going into these cards to understand why.

5060 and 5060Ti use the GB206 (should be 207) chip, which has a mere 4608 cores. For comparison, the GA106 chip used in the 3060 12GB had 3840 cores. GB206 also has a smaller memory bus at 128-bit, down from 192-bit on the GA106. Most of the uplift in performance is from higher boost clocks as you'll see for the rest of the lineup, and there is even a slight IPC regression. In another universe the GB206 chip would be found in a 5050/5050Ti. 

5070 uses the GB205 (should be 206) chip which has 6400 cores, and more importantly, a 192-bit bus. Compare this with GA104 (3070Ti) which had 6144 on 256-bit. This is effectively a 5060Ti at best, but realistically it's a 5060, because the 60Ti/Super has always used a higher-tier chip.

GB203 (should be 204) has 10752 cores, and the 5070Ti uses the lowest bin with 8960 cores. This is our hypothetical 5060Ti in another universe. This is also the chip that would be going into the 5070. In other words, the 5080 is actually a 5070. Are you surprised yet?

The actual GB203 chip does not exist. It should, but it does not.

GB202 is the largest chip in the desktop Blackwell family, at 24,576 cores - more than double of GB203 GB204. It's unheard of- you see why there is a missing chip? Nvidia skipped the actual GB203 and dropped the naming scheme across the board by 1, hence the (should be...) in brackets. This hypothetical GB203 chip would have ~14,000-18,000 cores, on a 384-320 bit wide bus, and is the actual chip that would be going into the 5070Ti and 5080. Not even the 5080Ti, which currently does not exist. That would be on the GB202 chip on a bin with fewer than 21760 cores, or maybe the 5090 could've been the 5080Ti with a higher bin as the 5090- could go either way. The existing 5090 does not use the full GB202 chip at just 21760 cores; the full chip goes into servers. 

And if we were to compare silicon sizes: 
GB206 is 181mm^2 compared to GA106 at 276mm^2
GB205 is 263mm^2 compared to GA104 at 394mm^2
GB203 is 378mm^2 compared to GA103 at 496mm^2
GB202 is 750mm^2 compared to GA102 at 672mm^2

Notice how, across the board, the sizes on Blackwell are one tier below. What's worse, is Blackwell has a yet unreleased GB207 (actually 208) chip which should be even smaller than the 5060's GB206. This is probably this generation's 1030, which no doubt Nvidia will market as a 50/50Ti and sell for around $200. 

Additionally, GA102 (3080/3090/3090Ti) is not even the largest chip in the Ampere family - that would be GA100 which is a mammoth 826mm^2. There is no GB200 desktop GPU. It is sold exclusively to servers, and it's even bigger. 

Lastly, I'd like to talk a little about rising silicon prices. Yes, they are very real, and they do contribute to rising GPU costs with each generation, always has. But since the RTX 4000/Ada Lovelace, Nvidia went with a double-whammy of raising GPU prices proportionally to the rising silicon prices and then selling one tier below for each GPU that generation anyway. They wanted to have their cake and eat it too, which they did. RTX 5000/Blackwell is simply a continuation of that. Hence the hilariously out of proportion GPU price/performance the past two generations.

16% performance increase with price the same (slightly cheaper if you count the inflation) - BAD!

3060 with 16% generational uplift at the same MSRP but with effectively 75% price increase at retail was good? While the 5060 with 16% generational uplift and no price change while retail-buyable at MSRP is bad? 

Really hard to follow the astroturfing logic, but I guess a few hundred people out of the loop will nod their head with you so it was money well spent on the youtubers.

Look here is the actual story. NVidia had some really brilliant people who planned out a series of architecture shifts and improvements spread into two halves, one for the Pascal 10-series architecture and one for the Turing 20-series architecture. Those jumps are normally super rare - the last time something came out that dominated that hard was the 8800GT. There is no such thing as an innovation assembly line. It takes genuinely brilliant people to change the status quo. It's also not a constant trickle of innovation, it comes in huge infrequent jumps.

The 3060, which people say was good, was literally a 2060 Super in performance.

The 4060, which people say was bad, is literally a 2080 in performance outside of maxing out settings at 1440p+. If you're playing at 1080p or 1440p medium-high, in many games the 4060 beats the pants off the 2080 and in a good amount of games beats even the 2080 Ti.

We will see how the 5060 shakes out after a year of driver optimizations, but generational GPU improvement is a function of 1) how fast the global foundries improve their nodes and 2) Innovation as a result of enormous thought time and money, which is driven by competition.

If you view a 60-class card as a 1080p card with the option for 1440p with lowered settings, the 5060 is exactly that card. If you've never played a computer game before and don't know that you can turn down graphics options slightly for massive performance increases and to remove a bottleneck, then now you know. Turn off raytracing and crazy lighting toggles, turn settings down a single notch across the board, bam it's a 1440p card. Play something that isn't a console port BAM 1440p max settings card.
